---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
import ProjectMetadata from '../../components/ProjectMetadata.astro';
import ImagePlaceholder from '../../components/ImagePlaceholder.astro';
import InfoGrid from '../../components/InfoGrid.astro';
import CaseStudyBlockquote from '../../components/CaseStudyBlockquote.astro';

const sections = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview' },
  { id: 'the-problem', label: 'The Problem' },
  { id: 'discovery--insights', label: 'Discovery & Insights' },
  { id: 'solution', label: 'Solution' },
  { id: 'achievements', label: 'Achievements' },
  { id: 'whats-next', label: "What's Next" },
  { id: 'learnings', label: 'Learnings' },
];
---

<ProjectLayout
  title="Account Abstraction | Tatiana Hernandez"
  description="Redesigning Web3 Trading: Making It Finally Make Sense"
  sections={sections}
>
  <!-- Project header -->
  <div class="flex flex-col gap-8">
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h4>Moralis • UX Case Study</h4>
      <h1>Redesigning Web3 Trading: Making It Finally Make Sense</h1>
      <p class="opacity-60">A UX Case Study On Account Abstraction And Trade Widget</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Hero thumbnail -->
    <div class="w-full aspect-[16/9] border-1 border-foreground/10">
      <div class="relative w-full h-full overflow-hidden" role="img" aria-label="Project thumbnail for Account Abstraction">
        <ImagePlaceholder color="#1A244550" />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Project metadata -->
    <ProjectMetadata
      role="Lead Product Designer"
      timeline="2022 – 2025"
      team="Cross-functional"
      skills={['Product Design', 'UX Research', 'Web3 UX']}
    />
  </div>

  <!-- Case study content -->
  <div class="flex flex-col gap-12">

    <!-- Overview -->
    <section id="overview" class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h4 class="!text-foreground mb-1">Overview</h4>
      <p>Moralis Money helps crypto users discover tokens before they trend — but once they did, trading them felt slow, complex, and disconnected. With a growing user base of active token hunters, the gap between discovery and trade was costing us conversions every day.</p>

      <InfoGrid items={[
        { title: 'The business context', desc: 'Moralis Money had built a strong discovery engine — users could spot trending tokens early. But the product stopped short of the moment that mattered most: the trade itself. Every user who left to complete a trade on a DEX was a potential churned user.' },
        { title: 'My role', desc: 'Lead a design exploration that solved two challenges: simplify the end-to-end trading experience, and make account abstraction — smart contract-based trading accounts — understandable and usable for mainstream crypto users.' },
      ]} />

      <CaseStudyBlockquote class="mt-4">What is account abstraction? Smart contract wallets that eliminate seed phrases and MetaMask pop-ups — enabling a smoother, more controlled trading experience that traditional EOA wallets can't offer.</CaseStudyBlockquote>
    </section>

    <!-- The Problem -->
    <section id="the-problem" class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h4 class="!text-foreground mb-1">From Discovery to Drop-off</h4>
      <h2 class="-mb-2">Why Were Users Not Completing Trades — And What Was It Costing Us.</h2>

      <h4 class="!text-foreground mt-8">The experience (Before)</h4>
      <p>Users came to Moralis to discover trending tokens...But when it came time to trading, they had to:</p>
      <InfoGrid columns={3} items={[
        { title: 'Copy the token address', desc: 'Manually copy the contract address from Moralis before they could do anything else.' },
        { title: 'Leave Moralis and open a DEX', desc: 'Navigate away to a separate platform like Uniswap to actually place the trade.' },
        { title: 'Reconnect their wallet', desc: 'Re-authenticate on the new platform, adding yet another friction point.' },
      ]} />
      <InfoGrid columns={3} class="mt-0" items={[
        { title: 'Search for the token again', desc: 'Re-find the same token they had already discovered on Moralis.' },
        { title: 'Manually complete the trade', desc: 'Finally execute the trade after navigating a completely separate product flow.' },
      ]} />

      <h4 class="!text-foreground mt-8">Before vs. After</h4>
      <p>Five steps across two platforms became a single, in-context action.</p>
      <div class="relative w-full bg-foreground-light/10 animate-pulse overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-full aspect-[16/9]" style="background-color:#1A244520;"></div>
      </div>

      <CaseStudyBlockquote class="mt-4">But it was slow, clunky, and confusing.</CaseStudyBlockquote>

      <p>Result? Users Dropped Off Before Ever Making A Trade. Every Exit Meant Lost Conversions And Reduced Retention.</p>

      <h2 class="-mb-2">And Reimagined The Entire Trading Journey From Scratch.</h2>
      <div class="relative w-full bg-foreground-light/10 animate-pulse overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-full aspect-[16/9]" style="background-color:#1A244520;"></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Discovery & Insights -->
    <section id="discovery--insights" class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h4 class="!text-foreground mb-1">Discovery & Insights</h4>
      <h2 class="-mb-2">Research that drove our design direction.</h2>
      <p>We ran user interviews and flow analytics to understand pain points. We learned:</p>
      <InfoGrid items={[
        { title: "Users didn't understand why they needed to activate a trading account", desc: 'The concept of account abstraction was invisible — users had no mental model for what a "trading account" was or why it was different from their existing wallet. Without that context, the activation step felt like a bug, not a feature.' },
        { title: 'Multiple steps created friction', desc: 'Copying addresses, switching platforms, MetaMask pop-ups — each step was a potential exit point that eroded user confidence and completion rates. The more steps between discovery and trade, the lower the conversion.' },
      ]} />
      <p class="mt-4">These insights drove our design direction.</p>
      <div class="relative w-full bg-foreground-light/10 animate-pulse overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-full aspect-[16/9]" style="background-color:#1A244520;"></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Solution -->
    <section id="solution" class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h4 class="!text-foreground mb-1">Solution</h4>
      <h2 class="-mb-2">Designing a Seamless Web3 Trading Experience</h2>
      <p>From Confusion To Clarity — How We Made Trading Intuitive Again In Three Steps.</p>

      <h4 class="!text-foreground mt-8">#1 — Widget</h4>
      <p>We created an embedded trade widget users could access from any screen. We A/B tested it against a fullscreen version and found the sidebar format increased trading activity and kept users in context.</p>
      <div class="relative w-full bg-foreground-light/10 animate-pulse overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-full aspect-[16/9]" style="background-color:#1A244520;"></div>
      </div>

      <h4 class="!text-foreground mt-8">#2 — Sidebar Experience</h4>
      <p>We presented a trading sidebar accessible from any Moralis Money screen. The sidebar includes fields for selecting the buy and sell tokens, integrating our token search (so users were able to find trending tokens and immediately trade them).</p>
      <div class="relative w-full bg-foreground-light/10 animate-pulse overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-full aspect-[16/9]" style="background-color:#1A244520;"></div>
      </div>

      <h4 class="!text-foreground mt-8">#3 — Account Abstraction Onboarding</h4>
      <p>Onboarding flow designed to deploy and activate the "Trading Account" via account abstraction. We guide the user from the welcome screen to depositing funds and confirming that their smart account is ready, reducing friction with clear messages and animations.</p>
      <p>The key design decision: explain what a trading account <em>does for you</em>, not what it <em>is</em> technically. Users don't need to understand smart contracts — they need to understand why this unlocks a better trading experience.</p>
      <div class="relative w-full bg-foreground-light/10 animate-pulse overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-full aspect-[16/9]" style="background-color:#1A244520;"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="h-[1px] w-full bg-foreground/10 mt-16 mb-8"></div>
    </section>

    <!-- Achievements -->
    <section id="achievements" class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h4 class="!text-foreground mb-1">Achievements</h4>
      <p>During this exploration, we conducted usability tests with prototypes across multiple rounds of testing. The results were clear: participants who went through the guided onboarding understood the trading account concept significantly better than those who encountered the previous experience — which simply launched a technical MetaMask window with no explanation or context.</p>

      <InfoGrid items={[
        { title: 'Higher comprehension', desc: 'Most participants understood what a trading account was and why they needed it — a sharp improvement over the baseline experience where users were left confused by a raw MetaMask prompt.' },
        { title: 'Fewer drop-offs during activation', desc: 'The guided onboarding flow reduced abandonment at the account activation step, the highest-friction point in the original flow.' },
        { title: 'A/B test validation', desc: 'The sidebar widget format outperformed the fullscreen version in trading activity — users stayed in context and completed more trades.' },
      ]} />

      <div class="relative w-full bg-foreground-light/10 animate-pulse overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-full aspect-[16/9]" style="background-color:#1A244520;"></div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="-mb-2">More engagement. Higher conversions. A Foundation For Advanced Trading.</h2>
      <p>Our design exploration significantly improved the user experience and product strategy of Moralis. We collaborated with the product team to envision a more advanced trading experience within Moralis, leveraging the flexibility of the smart trading account.</p>
      <div class="relative w-full bg-foreground-light/10 animate-pulse overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-full aspect-[16/9]" style="background-color:#1A244520;"></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- What's Next -->
    <section id="whats-next" class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h4 class="!text-foreground mb-1">What's Next</h4>
      <p>With a validated foundation in place, we worked with the product team to explore what a more advanced trading experience could look like — one that served power users without sacrificing the simplicity we had built for newcomers.</p>

      <h2 class="-mb-2">What if we provided users with professional-grade tools while maintaining simplicity?</h2>
      <p>High-impact business ideas emerged from sessions with the product team and power-user interviews: enabling automatic orders based on price alerts, copy-trading (mimicking expert wallets' trades), and customizable panels with market data.</p>
      <div class="relative w-full bg-foreground-light/10 animate-pulse overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-full aspect-[16/9]" style="background-color:#1A244520;"></div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="-mb-2">What if we provided users a standalone trading screen, with customizable widgets?</h2>
      <p>We explored a dedicated trading screen where users could configure their own workspace: live trading pair chart, user's "saved tokens" list, trending tokens, recent relevant transactions, among others. Early concept testing with active traders showed strong interest in this direction.</p>
      <div class="relative w-full bg-foreground-light/10 animate-pulse overflow-hidden">
        <div class="w-full aspect-[16/9]" style="background-color:#1A244520;"></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Learnings -->
    <section id="learnings" class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h4 class="!text-foreground mb-1">Learnings</h4>
      <p>This initiative not only expanded the functionality of Moralis Money but also solidified its position as an essential tool for traders and developers in the crypto ecosystem. Here are some key learnings from my experience:</p>
      <InfoGrid items={[
        { title: 'In Web3, the mental model gap is the real UX problem.', desc: 'Users don\'t need to understand smart contracts — they need to understand what they unlock. Every time we explained account abstraction in technical terms, we lost users. Every time we framed it around the benefit ("no more MetaMask pop-ups, no more copying addresses"), they leaned in. The design challenge wasn\'t the UI — it was the translation.' },
        { title: 'Context collapse kills conversions.', desc: 'Asking users to leave your product to complete its core action is a bet you will almost always lose. Bringing trading in-context — into the sidebar, into the same screen where they discovered the token — wasn\'t just a UX improvement. It was a product strategy shift that kept users inside the Moralis ecosystem at the most valuable moment.' },
        { title: 'Onboarding is product positioning.', desc: "The account abstraction onboarding wasn't just a setup flow — it was the moment users decided whether they trusted Moralis with their trades. How we explained the trading account shaped how users thought about the entire product. Getting that framing right was as important as getting the UI right." },
      ]} />

      <CaseStudyBlockquote class="mt-8">The trading widget and account abstraction onboarding were handed off to engineering and integrated into the Moralis Money product roadmap.</CaseStudyBlockquote>
    </section>

  </div>
</ProjectLayout>

<script>
  import { initMediaReveal } from '../../scripts/media-reveal';
  initMediaReveal();
</script>
